<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>CSS Properties Example</title>
    <style>
        /* Styling for the first example */
        .example1 {
            font-size: 10px; /* Text size is 10px */
            text-transform: uppercase; /* Text will appear in uppercase */
            font-family: cursive; /* Cursive font family */
            display: inline-block; /* Inline block behavior */
            height: 50vh; /* Fixed height of 10px */
            width: 50vw; /* Fixed width of 10px */
            background-color: red; /* Red background color */
            border: 5px solid black; /* Red border with 2px thickness */
            border-radius: 10%; /* Circular shape */
            font-weight: bold; /* Bold text */
            text-align: center; /* Text alignment for multiline text */
            line-height: 20px;
        }

        /* Styling for the second example with rem, vw, vh, % */
        .example2 {
            font-size: 1rem; /* Font size relative to root element */
            text-transform: capitalize; /* Capitalizes the first letter of each word */
            font-family: cursive; /* Cursive font family */
            display: inline-block; /* Behaves like a block but stays inline */
            height: 50vh; /* Height is 10% of the viewport height */
            width: 50vw; /* Width is 10% of the viewport width */
            background-color: red; /* Red background color */
            border: 2px solid red; /* Red border */
            border-radius: 10%; /* Circular shape */
            font-weight: bolder; /* Extra bold text */
            text-align: center; /* Center-aligns the text */
            line-height: 20px; /* space between line */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Example 1: Using fixed pixel sizes -->
    <div class="example1">A paragraph is defined as “a group of sentences or a single sentence that forms a unit” (Lunsford and Connors 116). Length and appearance do not determine whether a section in a paper is a paragraph. For instance, in some styles of writing, particularly
    journalistic styles, a paragraph can be just one sentence long.</div>

    <!-- Example 2: Using relative units (rem, vh, vw) -->
    <div class="example2">A paragraph is defined as “a group of sentences or a single sentence that forms a unit” (Lunsford and Connors 116). Length and appearance do not determine whether a section in a paper is a paragraph. For instance, in some styles of writing,
    particularly journalistic styles, a paragraph can be just one sentence long.</div>
</body>
</html>


1. font-size: 10px;
This property sets the size of the text to 10 pixels.

2. text-transform: uppercase;
This property transforms all text into uppercase letters.

3. font-family: cursive;
This property changes the font to a cursive style.

4. display: inline-block;
This property makes the element behave like a block element but still allows it to sit inline with other elements.

5. height: 10px;
This sets the height of the element to 10 pixels. You can also use other units like rem, vw, vh, or %:

rem: Relative to the root element's font size.
vw: 1% of the viewport width.
vh: 1% of the viewport height.
%: Percentage of the parent element.



6. width: 10px;
This sets the width of the element to 10 pixels.


7. background-color: red;
This property sets the background color of the element.



8. border: 2px solid red;
This adds a border around the element with:

2px thickness,
solid style,
and red color.



9. border-radius: 50%;
This makes the element’s corners rounded. Setting it to 50% creates a perfect circle (if width and height are equal).



10. font-weight: bold;
This makes the text bold. Other values include:

normal: Regular weight.
bolder: Extra bold weight.



11. text-align: justify;
This aligns the text so that it fits evenly on both left and right margins.

Other values:

left: Aligns text to the left.
right: Aligns text to the right.




